Daily Report 
<DATE1>  20 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Li Peng Presides Over High-Level Meeting on Floods </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Li Peng Presides Over High-Level Meeting on Floods </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2006140794 Beijing XINHUA in English 1350 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2006140794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, June 20 (XINHUA) -- Chinese Premier Li 
Peng presided over a meeting here today to draw up detailed 
plans for flood relief and prevention work in some southern 
Chinese provinces and autonomous regions. 
  Other Chinese Communist Party and government officials, 
including vice-premiers Zou Jiahua and Li Lanqing, took part in 
the meeting. 
  Instructions from Chinese President Jiang Zemin on the 
current flood control and relief work were passed on at the 
meeting. 
  Participants also listened to reports about the present 
anti- 
flood and relief work from departments such as the State Flood 
Control and Drought Relief Headquarters, the Ministry of Water 
Resources, the Ministry of Civil Affairs, the State Planning 
Commission, the Ministry of Health, the Ministry of Agriculture, 
the Ministry of Finance and the Central Meteorological Station. 
  In April and May, serious floods occurred in east China's 
Jiangxi and Fujian provinces, and in central China's Hunan 
Province. Entering June, the most serious floods were reported 
to have occurred on the Xijiang River of southwest China's 
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, the Beijiang River in south 
China's Guangdong Province and Xiangjiang River in Hunan 
Province. A large number of areas have been affected. 
  Premier Li said the Chinese Communist Party Central 
Committee 
and the State Council were paying close attention to the flood 
situations in these areas. 
  Party and government departments of all levels in the 
affected areas are all mobilizing the cadres and ordinary 
citizens, the Chinese [People's] Liberation Army men and the 
armed policemen to help prevent and control floods, as well as 
to provide relief in disaster-hit areas. 
  To make a success of flood control and disaster relief work, 
the meeting has also decided to send special working groups, 
formed by Vice-Premier Zou Jiahua, Wen jiabao, member of the 
secretariat of the Chinese Communist Party Central Committee, 
and State Councillor Chen Junsheng, to join local officials, 
army men and local people in Guangdong, Guangxi, Hunan and 
Jiangxi in flood control and disaster relief work. 
  The Chinese premier stressed that the priority of current 
flood control work should be to guarantee the safety of the 
grand embankment along the Beijiang River and embankment 
projects in Zhujiang (Pearl) River delta, to rescue residents 
besieged by floods as quickly as possible, and to ensure that 
people in flood-hit areas have enough to eat and wear and to 
prevent epidemics breaking out. 
  The premier also urged local officials to help people to 
resume production as soon as possible and rebuild their 
communities. 
  The flood control work of this year has just begun and the 
main flood season starts in late July and early August, while 
serious droughts were also reported to have hit some other 
areas, said the premier, urging that different localities must 
be well prepared for major floods and the most serious droughts. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

