<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Authorities Issue No. 2 Flood Bulletin </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Authorities Issue No. 2 Flood Bulletin </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1706141494 Beijing XINHUA in English 1347 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1706141494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, June 17 (XINHUA) -- The latest news from 
the State Flood Control and Drought Relief Headquarters 
indicates that the Xijiang River in southern China today rose to 
its highest level in four decades. 
  The No. 2 flood bulletin of the year, issued by China's 
highest authority for fighting floods, said that on June 16 the 
third highest water level appeared near Liuzhou city along the 
river, one of the three major tributaries of the Zhujiang 
(Pearl) River. 
  After the water level receded some time later, the river saw 
an even bigger flood peak at one o'clock this afternoon. The 
level reached 89.25 m, 9.25 m above warning stage, and the water 
flow reached 27,500 cubic meters per second. 
  The water level along the reaches of Wuzhou city was 23.48 m 
at two o'clock this afternoon, 8.48 m above the warning stage, 
and the waters have continued to rise. 
  In the above-mentioned areas, 146 industrial enterprises 
have 
been flooded and 46 reservoirs damaged, according to the 
bulletin. People threatened by the flood have been transferred 
to other, safer places. 
  The bulletin also said that on June 16, most of the heavy 
rains in China poured down on the watersheds of the Xijiang, 
Beijiang, Ganjiang, Xiangjiang and Minjiang rivers. Average 
precipitation was about 50 mm and surpassed 100 mm in some 
places. 
  Because of the rain, water levels in these rivers are 1-8 
meters above the warning stage. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-26173 </DOCNO>
