<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Reiterates Hope To Join UN </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Minister Reiterates Hope To Join UN </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1706135794 Taipei CNA in English 1322 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1706135794 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Willie Chu and Y.C. Tsai] </F>
  [Text] San Francisco, June 16 (CNA) -- The Republic of 
China [ROC] hopes to join the United Nations in order to make 
more contributions to the prosperity and stability of the 
Asia-Pacific region, ROC Foreign Affairs Minister Frederick 
Chien said Thursday [16 June]. 
  Chien made the statement in a panel discussion of the 1994 
world forum in Beaver Creek, Colorado. The forum opened 
Thursday and will continue through Saturday. 
  The forum, sponsored by the American Enterprise Institute, 
annually brings together more than 100 ranking government 
officials, senior business executives, and renowned academics 
from around the world to exchange views on the world's major 
concerns ranging from politics and regional security to economic 
issues. 
  Dignitaries attending the 1994 forum include former U.S. 
President Gerald Ford, Former French President Valery Giscard 
d'Estaing and former British Prime Minister James Callaghan. 
  During the panel discussion entitled "Asia at Center Stage 
-- 
Trade, Security, and Human Rights," Chien noted that Asia is 
expected to contribute 50 percent to global economic growth in 
the next decade. 
  Asia, which currently outperforms other world areas in 
employment and inflation, is a major source of the U.S. trade 
deficit, he pointed out, adding that how to narrow the trade 
imbalance has become a major concern. 
  Moreover, he said, the ROC has played an important role in 
the stability of the Asia-Pacific region. He also stressed that 
the investments made by Taiwan manufacturers in Mainland China 
have had a strong impact on the development of the mainland 
economy. 
  The panel discussion was chaired by James Lilly, former 
director of the Taipei office of the American Institute in 
Taiwan and former U.S. ambassador to Beijing. 
  Chien, accompanied by his wife, arrived in Beaver Creek 
Wednesday. This is the fourth consecutive year Chien has 
attended the forum. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

