<H3> <TI>   Official Urges Overseas Chinese To Help Economy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official Urges Overseas Chinese To Help Economy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK2006083894 Beijing CHINA DAILY in English 20 Jun 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> HK2006083894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing CHINA DAILY </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Sun Shangwu: "Group Aims To Improve the Economy"] </F>
  [Text] Serving the country's economic development will be 
the top priority of the All-China Federation of Returned 
Overseas Chinese, said a top official with the group. 
  Getting overseas Chinese involved in mainland projects will 
be encouraged, Yang Taifang, the newly-elected chairman, said at 
the final session of the federation's fifth national conference 
in Beijing on Saturday. 
  Co-operation with the overseas Chinese will be expanded to 
trade, science and technology, culture and education as well as 
hygiene and sports. 
  Yang encouraged returned overseas Chinese to join the 
country's policy-making process. 
  In January, 1991, the Chinese People's Political 
Consultative 
Conference, China's top advisory body, for the ruling party and 
government, accepted the federation as a group participant. 
  Yang vowed at the meeting to develop the federation into a 
"home to returned Chinese and their relatives." 
  Yang, 67, is the former minister of Posts and 
Telecommunications and has wide connections with overseas 
Chinese. 
  To draft the laws pertaining to overseas Chinese, 
legislators 
must solicit opinions and suggestions from them. The 
federation, in turn, will support the government's efforts to 
protect the interests and rights of overseas Chinese and their 
relatives, he said. 
  If necessary, the legislature will set up new projects, Yang 
added. 
  He also said the NPC [National People's Congress] has sent 
several teams to investigate and prepare to draft laws that will 
protect overseas Chinese investors. 

</TEXT>

