<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reform of Oil Distribution System Continuing `Smoothly' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reform of Oil Distribution System Continuing `Smoothly' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1706154794 Beijing XINHUA in English 1452 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1706154794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, June 17 (XINHUA) -- The reform of China's 
distribution system for crude and refined oils is going on 
smoothly. 
  From May 1, China instituted reforms of its distribution 
system for crude and refined oils so as to stabilize oil prices 
and normalize oil transactions on the market, rationally 
allocate oil resources and promote the production of crude oil. 
  In the past month, despite planned rises in prices of crude 
oil, retail sales prices of refined oil all over the country had 
declined due to the reduction of intermediate links in the 
distribution of refined oil. 
  Sources said that at present, the oil prices and oil market 
in China are stable and the channel between supply and demand is 
unblocked. 
  The reform of China's oil distribution focuses on the 
balance 
between supply and demand in oil production and consumption and 
coordination between domestic and international oil resources 
and the oil market; rational allocation of crude oil processing 
resources and refined oil resources; maintenance of rational oil 
price differences according to regional differences. 
  The reform also aims to reduce the intermediate links in oil 
distribution, unclog oil distribution channels and set up risk 
price funds for crude and refined oils. 
  The State Council stressed that from now on the state will 
exercise unified control over the prices of crude and refined 
oils. 
  All refineries must implement the sales prices of refined 
oils set by the state and all gas stations must strictly follow 
the stipulated oil prices in sales transactions. 
  No party, government or military organizations are permitted 
access to the wholesale or retail sale of crude oil and refined 
oil. 
  The State Council also stressed the role of the sales 
department of the China National Petrochemical Corporation as a 
main channel in the distribution of refined oil. 
  The government also stipulated that the refineries will 
directly supply big oil-consuming sectors including railways, 
transportation, civil aviation, armed forces and oil export 
companies. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-26222 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi118_n_94029" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-118 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  17 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Investors Eye Agricultural Projects </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Investors Eye Agricultural Projects </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1706133794 Beijing XINHUA in English 1321 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1706133794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Harbin, June 17 (XINHUA) -- An increasing number of 
potential overseas investors are turning their eyes to China's 
agricultural development projects. 
  In the recent influx of foreign investment, the construction 
of a new foreign-funded farm, the country's biggest in farm 
production joined by overseas firms, has started in the vast 
stretches of land under the jurisdiction of Fujin city, in 
northeast China's Heilongjiang Province. 
  The project, covering an area of 38,000 hectares of 
wasteland, was jointly financed by China and the Republic of 
Korea with investments totalling 227 million yuan (26.7 million 
U.S. dollars). It is expected to be completed in three years and 
provide an annual grain output of 105,000 tons. 
  According to an official with the provincial agricultural 
development department, in Heilongjiang there is a total of 8.6 
million hectares of farmland and 1.8 million hectares of 
cultivatable wasteland. The rich land resources are becoming a 
main attraction for overseas business people who seek to invest 
in China. 
  He said that the World Bank also has shown great interest in 
the development of arable lands in this area. It has approved 
loans of 120 million U.S. dollars in developing land resources 
in the province. 
  The loans will be used in cultivation of wastelands, 
improvement of low-yield lands and grasslands and processing of 
sideline products. The project will start in 1997. 
  Also, a Thai- and Malaysian-funded project involving 10 
million U.S. dollars is being built in Hulin County of the 
province. When the farm is completed, all its sideline products 
will be exported. 
  To boost the development of its agriculture, the provincial 
government has implemented preferential policies for use of 
wastelands. 
  In other parts of China, including Liaoning and Jilin 
provinces also in the northeast, the local governments have also 
made efforts to encourage foreign investors to invest in 
agricultural projects, particularly in the processing of 
sideline products. 
  Xiao Zhuofu, vice-governor of Liaoning, said that his 
government has decided to select more farmlands for development 
by foreign firms. A farm experimental center will be built near 
Jinxi city to show how overseas investment has been attracted to 
the province, he said. 
  The Chinese central government has long paid attention to 
development and construction of grain production bases in 
northeast China. 
  Toward the end of the 1970s, one farm in Heilongjiang 
Province took out loans of one million U.S. dollars to import 
more than 60 sets of farm machinery. 
  Later, the country's first modernized farm, called "Honghe 
Farm," was built in this province with a loan of 110 million 
yuan from the Japanese Government in the form of compensation 
trade. About 20,000 hectares of wasteland were cultivated. The 
loan had been paid years ago with the soybeans produced in the 
farm, which is now affiliated with a new town. 
  So far, a number of such farms have been built in this vast 
fertile plain. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-26223 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi118_n_94030" </HT>


<HEADER>
