<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Taipei Rebuffs Beijing's Call for High-Level Meeting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Taipei Rebuffs Beijing's Call for High-Level Meeting </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1706134694 Taipei CNA in English 1328 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1706134694 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Benjamin Yeh] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, June 17 (CNA) -- Taipei on Friday [17 June] 
responded coolly to Beijing's call for a high-level meeting to 
promote cross-strait dialogue and rapprochement. 
  Kao Kung-lian, vice chairman of the Mainland Affairs 
Council, 
told a press conference that "there is no need for Taiwan to 
immediately respond to the mainland's urge to hold high-level 
talks or the fifth round of negotiations...because Taiwan's call 
for special negotiations to work out ways to safeguard Taiwan 
tourists on the mainland has been snubbed by Beijing." 
  "Taiwan on several occasions urged the mainland to talk over 
compensation for the 24 Taiwan tourists killed in March 31's 
Qiandao Lake crime, but ARATS [Association for Relations Across 
the Taiwan Strait] has yet to respond to our request," Kao said. 
  Wang Daohan, chairman of the Beijing-based Association for 
Relations Across the Taiwan Strait, faxed a message to C.F. Ku, 
president of Taipei's Straits Exchange Foundation (SEF) on 
Thursday recommending the two meet either in Taipei or a third 
place to tackle cross-strait issues. 
  ARATS again raised the proposal in another fax to the SEF on 
Friday. The two semi-official organizations are authorized by 
their respective governments to handle private exchanges between 
the two sides in the absence of official contacts. 
  Ku and Wang met in Singapore in April 1993 for the first 
time 
to lay a framework for SEF-ARATS exchanges. Several agreements 
were signed during the historic meeting. 
  Cross-strait relations have been severely strained due to 
the 
killings. 

</TEXT>

