<F P=102>   OW2106140794 Taipei CNA in English 1350 GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2106140794 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Benjamin Yeh] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, June 21 (CNA) -- Taiwan has decided to 
provide NT [new Taiwan] $10 million (US$370,370) worth of food 
and medicine to Mainland China to help flood victims there. 
  "The purchase of relief materials is expected to be 
completed 
in a week and forwarded to the mainland," said Chang Sung-mao, 
secretary-general of the Red Cross Society of the Republic of 
China [ROC]. 
  Chang said he had contacted Sun Bochiu and Qu Zhe, vice 
presidents of the Red Cross Society's mainland chapter, upon 
learning of the recent floods. 
  "They told me that the damage brought by the floods is 
serious and expressed hope that Taiwan can lend help," Chang 
said. 
  According to foreign wire-service reports, 438 people have 
been killed and 6,470 others injured in six provinces in south 
China over the past 12 days, with Guangdong and Hunan Provinces 
being hardest hit. In addition, 480,000 houses have been 
destroyed and 3 million hectares of rice paddies washed away, 
with total property losses estimated at US$2 billion. 

</TEXT>

