<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   Beijing Says Mission Staff Recruitment Not Studied </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Beijing Says Mission Staff Recruitment Not Studied </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK2006064794 Hong Kong HONGKONG STANDARD in English 20 Jun 
94 p 4 </F>

<F P=103> HK2006064794 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong HONGKONG STANDARD </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By M.Y. Sung in Beijing] </F>
  [Text] China has dismissed diplomatic concerns that it 
might plant spies and informers in foreign consulates in Hong 
Kong after 1997. 
  Diplomatic missions in the territory fear a Foreign 
Ministry-run government agency might centralise their supply of 
local staff when Hong Kong reverts to Chinese rule in 1997. 
  Under the Basic Law, the Central People's Government will be 
responsible for foreign affairs in the Special Administrative 
Region (SAR). 
  But China's Ministry of Foreign Affairs told The HONGKONG 
STANDARD it had no intention of changing current consulate 
practices which allow foreign diplomatic missions in the 
territory absolute freedom to recruit their own staff. 
  In a statement, the Foreign Ministry said all 
consulate-related matters would be further examined, but that 
basically China was unwilling to change the territory's usual 
practices. 
  "After China's resumption of the exercise of sovereignty 
over 
Hong Kong, the present system will basically remain unchanged," 
the Foreign Ministry said. 
  Staff such as office clerks, interpreters, drivers or 
domestic helpers at diplomats' residences are usually recruited 
through public advertisements in local newspapers. 
  Sources argued the practice of planting bugs and spies in 
foreign diplomatic missions was not only used by communist 
countries but also by many Western nations. 
  "Under the present staff recruitment rules, spies and 
informers can still mingle in foreign consulates in Hong Kong," 
a source said. 
  The question of whether new recruitment rules will be 
introduced for the territory's foreign consulates is a very 
"minor issue to China. 
  "A principle has been stipulated under the Basic Law on the 
questions concerning the establishment of foreign consulates in 
Hong Kong," the Foreign Ministry statement said. 
  Foreign Ministry spokesman Shen Guofeng explained that 
foreign affairs issues in Hong Kong would be handled by China 
under the Basic Law provisions which referred to major 
diplomatic policy. 
  "The Foreign Ministry will not take care of those small 
concrete things," Mr Shen said, referring to staff recruitment 
for foreign diplomatic missions in Hong Kong. 
  "The local staff recruitment rules for consulates are among 
considerable number of matter that have not yet been fully 
studied by the Foreign Ministry." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-26375 </DOCNO>
